# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aorangi-forest-park
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The area of the park has seen human interaction for approximately 700 years, with evidence of habitation dating back to early Māori iwi such as Waitaha and Rapuwai during the early periods of Māori habitation in New Zealand.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Following the arrival of Pākehā in the 19th century, the area saw widespread deforestation, farming, and quarrying, significantly modifying the area's environment.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this, the park is one of the most modified landscapes of any of New Zealand's national parks, with management of the park largely focusing on regeneration and restoration of the traditional ecosystem.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was first established in 1942 to commemorate the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's 1642 visit in New Zealand, when he became the first European to sight the islands.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It has since been progressively expanded from its original borders, the most recent of which involved the addition of 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet after a successful crowdfunding campaign.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The coastal area was inhabited for hundreds of years by Māori prior to the arrival of Europeans, with sites throughout the area occupied both seasonally and permanently.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In addition to harvesting food from the local forests, estuaries and waters, locals grew kūmara.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Historical records indicate a pā was established at Auckland Point by Pohea, who travelled there around 1450 from the Whanganui area.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] From the mid-1500s Muaūpoko (formerly known as Ngāi Tara) occupied the area until the early 1600s, when they were ousted by Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri were present when Abel Tasman reached Golden Bay / Mohua in 1642.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was founded in 1942, largely through the efforts of ornithologist and author Pérrine Moncrieff to have land reserved for the purpose.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Moncrieff served on the park board from 1943 to 1974.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was opened on 18 December 1942 to mark the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's visit.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Those in attendance at the opening ceremony at Tarakohe included Charles van der Plas, as personal representative of the Netherlands' Queen, Wilhelmina.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The idea for the park had been under consideration since June 1938.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Crown set aside 15,225 hectares (37,622 acres), comprising 8,900 hectares (21,900 acres) of proposed state forest, 5,809 hectares (14,354 acres) of Crown land and 554 hectares (1,368 acres) of other reserve land for the national park.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Golden Bay Cement Company donated the land where the Abel Tasman Monument and a memorial plaque was sited.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The area's primary historic interest was the visit of Tasman in 1642, D'Urville in 1827, and the New Zealand Company barques *Whitby* and *Will Watch*, and brig *Arrow* in 1841.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The site was also of significant botanical interest.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] By 1946 the park had reached 15,534 hectares (38,386 acres) in area with additional land purchases.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] A further 844 hectares (2,085 acres) at Tōtaranui, formerly owned by William Gibbs, was acquired from J S Campbell in 1949 and added to the park.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] About 6,100 hectares (15,000 acres) have been added since.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2008 an extra 7.9 km2 (790 ha; 3.1 sq mi), including the formerly private land known as Hadfields Clearing, were added to the park.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2016, a further 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet was purchased by New Zealanders in a crowdfunding campaign.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Covering an area of 237 km2 (92 sq mi; 59,000 acres), the park is the smallest of New Zealand's national parks.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It consists of forested, hilly country to the north of the valleys of the Tākaka and Riwaka Rivers, and is bounded to the north by the waters of Golden Bay / Mohua and Tasman Bay.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains some of the islands off the coast including the Tata Islands in Golden Bay / Mohua, and Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island, and Fisherman Island in Tasman Bay.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park does not extend beyond Mean High Water Mark on the adjacent coast.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Between Mean High Water and Mean Low Water Springs, the beaches are gazetted as a Scenic Reserve, covering 7.74 km2 (2.99 sq mi) in total.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Tonga Island Marine Reserve adjoins part of the park.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Monument, though not located in the park, commemorates the first contact between Europeans and Māori and is located near the northern end of the park.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Abel Tasman National Park stands out from most other National parks of New Zealand, given that a large area of it has undergone extensive environmental modification in its history.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Early European settlers burned or cleared much of the forest, only to find that the soil was unsuitable for farming.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] This practise not only destroyed much of the shrubland and forests, but also introduced invasive plants found throughout the modern-day park.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] However, as time progresses, the original ecosystems and forests are slowly returning.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains varied habitats, including coastal forests, sub-alpine bogs, and sand dunes.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this diversity, many different species can be found.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The islands of the park, in particular Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island and Fisherman Island which are the largest, have been disturbed less and have no introduced mammalian predators.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result the islands have species not found elsewhere in the park and there are more restrictions to visitor access.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Though much of the parkland is pasture or covered with shrubs, valley areas contain forests of rātā, mataī, miro and hinau.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Over 70 species of birds have been recorded in the park.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Some of the birds that can frequently be seen are petrels, shags, penguins, gulls, terns, and herons.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Possums, wild pigs, deer, and goats can also be seen in the park.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Coast Track is a popular tramping track that follows the coastline and is one of the Department of Conservation's Great Walks; the Abel Tasman Inland Track is less frequented.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Other walks in the park, such as the Wainui Falls Track are considered "short walks".
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Kayaking, camping and sightseeing are other activities.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Access to the park is usually via the small settlement of Mārahau or Kaiteriteri (by water taxi).
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The nearest large town is Motueka, 20 kilometres (12 mi) to the south.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Dogs (excepting guide dogs) are not allowed in the park.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation administers the National Park.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Scenic Reserve is administered by the Tasman District Council Chief Executive and Department of Conservation's Nelson / Marlborough Conservator.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Activities in adjoining coastal waters are Tasman District Council's responsibility.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] These areas operate under separate regulations.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Interior, consisting of the park areas further inland.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Park plans include ecological surveys, pest control, and protection of heritage areas and caves.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Islands, encompassing all islands within the park, some of which are closed to the public. key priorities include keeping them free of invasive pests, reintroducing native species, and minimizing human impacts.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2012 Project Janszoon, a privately funded trust, was set up to restore the park's ecosystems.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The trust takes its name from Tasman's middle name *Janszoon*.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It is aiming to complete the restoration in time for the 400th anniversary of Tasman's visit and the park's 100th anniversary in 2042.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation and Project Janszoon developed a free virtual visitor centre for downloading to smartphones or tablets.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The application provides information about the Park's history, its flora and fauna, points of interest, weather, walking tracks, and tides.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/abel-tasman-national-park] This virtual visitor centre is free of charge and can be found through the App Store or Google Play Store.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] An **administrative centre** is a seat of regional administration or local government, or a county seat or town, or the place where the central administration of a commune or equivalent subdivision, is located.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] In countries with French as an administrative language, such as Belgium, Luxembourg, Switzerland and many African countries, a ***chef-lieu*** (French pronunciation: [ʃɛfljø], pl.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] 'chief place' or 'main place') is a town or city that is important from an administrative perspective.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The capitals of Algerian provinces, districts, and communes are called *chefs-lieux*.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The *chef-lieu* in Belgium is the administrative centre of each of the ten provinces of Belgium.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Three of these cities also give their name to their province (Antwerp, Liège and Namur).
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The *chef-lieu* of a French department is known as the prefecture (*préfecture*).
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] This is the town or city where the prefect of the department (and all services under their control) are situated, in a building also known as the prefecture.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] In every French region, one of the departments has preeminence over the others, and the prefect carries the title of *préfet de la région* (lit.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] 'Prefect of the Region') or *préfet du département* (lit.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] 'Prefect of the Department') and the city where the regional prefect is found is known as the *chef-lieu* of the region.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The services are, however, controlled by the prefecture of the department.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The *chef-lieu* of an arrondissement, commonly known as the *sous-préfecture* is the city or town where the sub-prefect of the arrondissement (and the services directly under their control) are situated, in a building called the sub-prefecture.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The arrondissement where the department prefecture is located does not normally have a sub-prefect or sub-prefecture, the administration being devolved usually to the secretary-general of the departmental prefecture, who functions as sub-prefect for the arrondissement.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The *chef-lieu* of a canton is usually the biggest city or town within the canton, but has only a nominal role.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] No specific services are controlled by it.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] In past decades, there was always a gendarmerie, a treasurer and a justice of the peace.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The *chef-lieu* indicates the principal city of the provinces of New Caledonia.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] So Nouméa is the chef-lieu of South Province.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] But the chef-lieu can also mean the principal area within a town.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] So Wé is part of the town of Lifou, but is the chef-lieu of Lifou.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] In the Loyalty Islands and the other islands, the name of the chef-lieu differs from that of the name of the town.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] For the towns of the mainland, the chef-lieu has the same name as the town.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Nouméa is a town composed only of Nouméa.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Many of the West African states which gained independence from France in the mid-20th century also inherited the French administrative structure of departments and communes, headed by a *chef-lieu*.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] States still using *chef-lieu* to identify the administrative headquarters of a government subdivision include Senegal, Burkina Faso, Benin, Mali, and Niger.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Taking Niger and Mali as examples, the administrative subdivisions down to the commune level each have a formal place of administrative headquarters, titled the *chef-lieu*.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The larger portion of the terminology of administrative division is inherited from colonial rule as part of French West Africa, and has survived and been somewhat modified over time.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] In both nations there have been remarkably parallel histories.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Since decentralization began in both nations in the 1990s, the *chef-lieu* transitioned from the location of the governor, commandant, or prefect and their staff to the location of the commune, cercle, department, and regional councils and a variety of decentralized bodies.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The **chef-lieu** of a region, cercle or department is usually also a communal **chef-lieu**.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Both nations also established a supreme council of local government authorities (*Haut conseil des collectivités territoriales*) seated at the nation's capital.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Smaller subdivisions in Mali's communes (villages, tribal councils, and quarters) are administered from a *place* (lit.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] 'site'), so the *chef-lieu* is literally the 'chief-place' even at the lowest level.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] In Jordan, the administrative centres are known as chief towns or *nahias*.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Nahias may be in charge of a sub-district (*qda*), a district (*liwa*), or a governorate (*muhafazah*).
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Luxembourg is divided into four electoral constituencies, twelve cantons, as well as 100 communes (Luxembourgish: *Gemengen*).
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Cantons have each a *chef-lieu* and are named after it.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The same is true for each commune which is composed of more than one town or village.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Usually, with a few exceptions, the commune is named after the communal *chef-lieu*.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] In Russia, several million-plus cities in federal districts have the official status of an administrative centre: Moscow (as the main city of the Central Federal District), Vladivostok, Volgograd, Yekaterinburg, Nizhny Novgorod, Novosibirsk, Pyatigorsk, Rostov-on-Don and St.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The main cities of regions and municipal districts are also called unofficially the administrative centre or simply the centre.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The only exception to this rule is the republics, for which the term "capital" is used to refer to the seat of government.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The capital of Russia is also an entity to which the term "administrative centre" does not apply.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] In Sweden there are two levels of administrative centre; the local municipal and the regional county.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Central locality (Swedish: *centralort*) is a term commonly ascribed to the settlement that serves as a municipal administrative centre.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] This level handles the local administrative and political tasks of the surrounding settlements.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Since central place theory was the guiding principle during the 1962–1977 municipal reform, most municipalities were dominated by a larger urban area where the political seat was located.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Most municipalities are named for their central locality, but there are several exceptions.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] There are many deviations from the central locality principle.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Some municipalities are dominated by two or more towns of similar size, and sometimes they share the municipal administration, with the municipality having its official address in one of the towns.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] For example, both Skillingaryd and Vaggeryd are central localities of Vaggeryd Municipality.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Conversely, there are municipalities within metropolitan areas.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] For example, there are twenty-six municipalities within the Stockholm metropolitan area.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The term "central locality" has no legal meaning and it is unclear how it should be applied to these municipalities.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Some municipalities appointing one or several localities to be the central locality.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] A residence city (Swedish: *residensstad*) is the town or city which is the political and administrative seat of the county.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] This level handles the more regional political and administrative tasks of the county, such as healthcare and public transport.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The name comes from these towns or cities being where the governor (*landshövding*) resides.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The term *chef-lieu* is applied to the capital of each Swiss canton.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] In 16 of the 26 cantons, the territory is subdivided into districts.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Every district's capital is also termed a *chef-lieu* and each has a prefect.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] The term *chef-lieu* is used to designate the capital of each governorate of Tunisia.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] Each of the 24 governorates is subdivided into delegations which each have a central city as the *chef-lieu* of the delegation.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] In the United Kingdom, an administrative centre is the centre of a local authority, which is distinct from the county town of a historic county.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/administrative-centre] For example, the administrative centre where the county council of Lancashire sits is Preston, even though the county town is Lancaster.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The mountains, forests, tussock lands and river valleys are used for tramping, fishing kayaking, horse riding and hunting.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Both the park and neighbouring Ben Avon Station are located near the Aoraki Mackenzie International Dark Sky Reserve, a dark-sky preserve, and are used for astronomy.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The town is serviced by the tourist town of Omarama.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The park was established in 2005, and includes the Birchwood Station leasehold farm the New Zealand Government bought back for NZ$10 million in 2004.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] It contained extensive wetlands that had remained largely undeveloped.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Birchwood Station continued normal farming operations until the end of the leasehold in 2010.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The road to the former Birchwood Station homestead stopped being regularly maintained by Waitaki District Council in 2011.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] In 2014, ecologist Peter Espie reported a decrease in native plant species in the park, and suggested introducing grazing management.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Parts of the 2020 Disney film *Mulan* were filmed in the Ahuriri Valley near the conservation park, including the training camp scenes and some battle scenes.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Akaroa Marine Reserve and the nearby Pōhatu Marine Reserve are no-take zones.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The harbour as a whole has considerable natural values, and the fauna of the inner and outer harbour differs.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] There are pressures on the ecology from human activity, such as settlements on the edge of the harbour, and land and water-based industrial activity.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The marine boundary of Akaroa Marine Reserve is almost entirely surrounded by Akaroa Taiāpure, which occupies the rest of the harbour and the ocean coast between the Akaroa and Pōhatu reserves.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure is a local fishing co-management tool for the harbour, which has customarily been of special significance to the hapū as a source of food for spiritual and cultural reasons.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure was established over 90 percent of the harbour in February 2006.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] It allows Te Rūnanga o Ngāi Tahu (tribal council) and other fisheries stakeholders to have a say in how the harbour is managed.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishing can continue in taiāpure, subject to rules and regulations.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure complements the reserve (the remaining 10% of the harbour), as does Pōhatu Marine Reserve just outside the harbour entrance, in Pōhatu / Flea Bay, plus Lyttelton Harbour's Port Levy Mātaitai Reserve and Rāpaki Mātaitai Reserve.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] A *mātaitai* is a permanent reserve created in areas of traditional importance to Māori for customary food gathering.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The two marine reserves are total no-take areas, whereas the taiāpure and mātaitai are fishing enabling and not about the protection of marine life.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Indeed, the *tangata tiaki* (marine guardian) has the power to override fishing regulations, and moreover, the taking of kelp by one pāua farmer is enshrined in the taiāpure legislation.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Akaroa Taiāpure Management Committee is a non-elected group largely made up of Ngāi Tahu representatives and a range of fisheries interest groups, including recreational, commercial, marine farmers and marine tourism operators.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] This committee has no control over the number of recreational anglers, hence no control over the total number of fish and shellfish taken.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Throughout the 1980s and 1990s, people with local knowledge knew that fish stocks were nowhere near as plentiful as they once were.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Māori who had fished the harbour for decades had lost the opportunity of fishing freely along its shoreline.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The *rūnanga* (committee of senior decision-makers of an *iwi* (tribal group) or *hapū* (family, district groups or community)) knew that pollution and over-fishing had diminished the area of available *mahinga kai* (traditional food gathering areas) within the harbour.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Pollution includes sewage, farm and sub-division run-off as well as algal blooms.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Forest and Bird carried out exploratory dives in Akaroa Harbour in 1990.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Akaroa Harbour Marine Protection Society formally proposed the establishment of a 560-hectare (1,400-acre) marine reserve in 1996.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The proposal was divisive and led to a two-decade battle that pitted a small group of vocal and determined local residents and divers against recreational anglers, *rūnanga*, commercial fishers and one aquaculturalist.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The local residents wanted a no-take area in the eastern waters of the outer harbour to acts as a breeding pool and as place for dolphins to feed.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Recreational anglers argued "that's where we fish in a northeasterly".
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Te Runanga o Ngāi Tahu claimed strong ties to the area, naming it Te Whata o Kōkiro (meaning the food store-house of Kokiro).
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] When the marine reserve idea was first mooted, commercial fishing was a part of Akaroa's economy and commercial fishers strongly opposed it.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] During the long battle, fish stock declined, and so did commercial fishing.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The original proposal called for a reserve within the harbour.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishers counteracted that proposal by applying for and getting a smaller 215 hectares (530 acres) hectares reserve to be located outside of the harbour, at sheltered bay named Pōhatu / Flea Bay.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] While eco-tourism operators were pleased to have something to show to tourists, local iwi continued to express concerns that marine reserves hindered their traditional rights to harvest from the sea.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Meanwhile, the local residents group continued to advocate for a reserve within the harbour.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Fisheries Act 1996 Part 9 Section 174–175 provides for the establishment of taiāpure/fisheries co-management by local people who care about and have strong ties to an area.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In January 2004, the Māori Land Court tribunal made a recommendation to the Minister of Fisheries that a taiāpure be granted over the whole of Akaroa Harbour bar one small area subject to the, at that time, proposed Akaroa Marine Reserve.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Judge Wainwright saw no reason why the two could not live together.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] However, this recommendation was successfully appealed by the local pāua farmer and kelp harvester, who claimed a taiāpure would compromise his business.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The High Court sent the case back to the tribunal to gather further evidence about whether the whole of Akaroa Harbour does or does not come within the concept of "littoral coastal waters" of "special cultural significance" to the rūnanga.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The pāua farmer eventually reached an understanding with Ngāi Tahu, ending years of argument.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] He has been granted the rights to harvest giant bladder kelp (*Macrocystis pyrifera*), which he uses to feed the pāua at the Akaroa Paua Farm and also to make garden fertiliser and kelp pepper.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In contrast, the East Otago Taiāpure explicitly prohibits the harvesting of kelp.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] That ban does not extend to unattached beach-cast kelp.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] There are environmental concerns in Akaroa Harbour regarding the ecological disruption caused by kelp harvesting to wild pāua and other *kaimoana* (sea food).
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure was established in February 2006, but the marine reserve took eight more years.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Conservation Minister Kate Wilkinson declined the application for the reserve in 2010 on the grounds that it would adversely affect recreational fishing.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The decision was challenged in the High Court and was quashed in a 2012 ruling.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In terms of actual numbers, the two separate consultation processes for the application had attracted more support than opposition.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In April 2013 Conservation Minister Nick Smith announced the approval of the reserve but at the reduced size of 465 hectares (1,150 acres).
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Smith believed the battle had gone on for too long.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The size was reduced to take into account the concerns about customary and recreational fishing.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Subsequently, the size was finalised as 512 hectares (1,270 acres).
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Environment Minister Amy Adams expressed an aspiration for the next step to be integrating the local management of taiāpure and reserve so the two mechanisms work together.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] New Zealand fishing rules place reduced bag limits on many fish species and prohibit shellfish gathering in specific areas.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Tangata tiaki (marine guardians) are appointed for Ōnuku Runanga *rōhe moana* (defined customary fishing area) by the Minister of Primary Industries.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The tangata tiaki (also known as kaitiaki) receive training in bylaws, what quantities of various species can be taken, dates or seasons recommended for harvest, size limits and methods of harvest.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishers can get a kaitiaki permit from the tangata tiaki granting permission to take over and above the catch limit, and under the legal size.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] This permit, colloquially called a "chit", is given for *tangihanga* (funeral), *hui* (gathering) and other occasions.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In addition to upping catch limits, the kaitiaki has the power to override other fishing regulations.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In 2018, the Department of Conservation trialled a baited underwater video study, which provided a snapshot of the fish communities both within and outside the Akaroa and Pōhatu marine reserves.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] A total of 28 fish species were identified, demonstrating that the baited underwater video technique is an effective method for examining the size and relative abundance of these species.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The study found notable differences in the relative abundances and sizes of blue cod and blue moki in the marine reserves when compared to three taiāpure control areas.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] However, since there is no baseline data for Akaroa Marine Reserve, it would be hasty to link these spatial variations to their protection status.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Nonetheless, the results indicated an increase in the abundance and size of blue cod and moki at Pōhatu reserve compared to earlier studies, and that is likely due to the protection from direct fishing pressure.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In 2021, a three-year initiative called *Iongairo* was launched to supply data that aids in the management of customary fishing zones and enhances understanding of marine reserves in Te Pātaka o Rākaihautū/Banks Peninsula.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] *Iongairo* focused on identifying and evaluating important habitats—including rock, sand, and mud—and key species such as pāua, mussels, and various types of seaweed.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Additionally, it examined the effects of human activities on the environment.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Methods included baited underwater cameras, towed and dropped cameras, along with sediment grabs.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The outcome is an interactive online map showcasing the seafloor.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akatarawa-forest] The park is owned and managed by Greater Wellington Regional Council, making it one of the largest landowners in New Zealand.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akatarawa-forest] Akatarawa is a Māori name meaning 'Trailing vines'.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akatarawa-forest] Activities include cycling, hunting, fishing, horse riding, 4WD-vehicle trips and trail biking, including at the Karapoti Gorge.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akatarawa-forest] Akatarawa Forest has ancient northern rātā which predate human habitation of New Zealand, including one tree which is believed to be 1100 years old.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akatarawa-forest] Some of these trees are wider than Tāne Mahuta.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akatarawa-forest] One is largest rātā tree in New Zealand, at 39 metres tall.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akatarawa-forest] Greater Wellington Regional Council carried out a 1080 dropping programme in 2013 to reduce pest species.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akatarawa-forest] A trailbiker was seriously injured in the park in July 2017.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akatarawa-forest] A dirt-biker was rescued from the forest in February 2021.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akatarawa-forest] Between December 2017 and August 2018, a 1.7 kilometre zig-zag track that is part of the Cannon Point Walkway was closed to the public due to a disagreement between Upper Hutt City Council and a private landowner over land access.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akatarawa-forest] In early 2021, Forest and Bird campaigned for Upper Hutt City Council to keep a 35-hectare block as a wildlife corridor and reserve, connecting Akatarawa Forest with Wainuiomata.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/akatarawa-forest] In July 2021, a further 1080 operation was carried out in 2021 to combat a resurgence in possum numbers.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The area was previously a defensive pā, built by Te Kawerau sub-tribes, occupied until as recently as 1827.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Ngāti Pāoa ceded the land to the Crown on 5 January 1854, which was subsequently granted to an Austrian, Captain Martin Krippner, in 1860.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] In the 1870s, Major de Grut took over the land until it was sold to the Eaves family in 1919.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The local Lions began making tracks, building bridges and removing invasive weeds, and the Reserve was formally opened by the Lions Club Chairman, Don Woods on 10 December 1960.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The daughters of Alice and Edward Eaves were present.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] A series of pedestrian walkways have been constructed through the reserve, as well as a wooden look out point over Orewa Beach that was built in 1997.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The reserve includes kauri trees as old as 300 years.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] In addition, the bush contains native trees such as tōtara, mataī, kahikatea, pūriri, rata, karaka, rimu, rewarewa, nīkau and taraire.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] A number of these trees can be identified by labels along the walkway.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Several small streams feed the Nukumea Stream, which marks the reserve's southern boundary.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The status of the land is Scenic Reserve 19(1)(a) and under the Reserves Act, the management is the responsibility of the Hibiscus and Bays Local Board, elected representatives under the Governing Body, Auckland Council.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The role of the Board is to make decisions on local matters such as the maintenance and upgrading of facilities, caring for the environment, preservation of heritage and supporting activities in the area.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] In June 2019, the Reserve was required by the Auckland Council to close to the public due to the danger of kauri dieback caused by the spread of a pathogen in contaminated soil possibly being carried on the soles of shoes.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Lauri Rands from the Eaves Bush Appreciation Society expressed sadness but noted that protection of the 800-year-old kauri in the Reserve was a good example of the importance of taking this action.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The lower track on the Reserve was re-opened on 30 August 2020 with a hygiene station at the entrance and exit to allow shoes to be cleaned.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] It was noted at the time, that the upper tracks were scheduled for re-opening late in 2021.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Hibiscus and Bays Local Board Chair Gary Brown expressed delight at the reopening and appreciation to the Council for the work they had done to bring this about.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] He also acknowledged the voluntary contribution of the Eaves Bush Appreciation Group who had worked for years to weed, plant and trap pests.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Members of this group were the first to walk the re-opened section.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The Greenways project proposed by the Auckland Council in 2016 had been prioritised by the Hisbiscus and Bays Local Board in 2017 and a feasibility report for implementing walking and cycling connections between the Reserve and Hatfields Beach was completed in 2018.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] The park is a working sheep and dairy farm with a woolshed and milking shed.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] There are also goats, cows, pigs, chickens, turkey, rabbits and peacocks.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] Areas of the park are leased to the Mangere Pony Club, and the Ambury Park Centre for Riding Therapy, a charity which opened in 1985, which provides physiological and psychological therapy through horse riding.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] The parks hosts the Ambury Farm Day each year.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] It is the largest annual event organised by Auckland Council, and gives families free access to a working farm.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] The park covers 85 hectares (210 acres) of low-lying volcanic land on the shores of the upper Manukau Harbour.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] It includes both camping coastline, grazed farming paddocks, wetlands, saltmarshes and small areas of native forest.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] Much of Ambury Regional Park formed approximately 50,000 years ago, during an eruption of Māngere Mountain.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] There are several examples of basalt lava flows, originating from the Māngere Mountain about 18,000 years ago.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] Most other lava flows around Auckland have been destroyed during urban development.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] Large numbers of migratory shorebirds visit Ambury Regional Park and the surrounding areas of the Manukau Harbour, with an estimated number of 28,000 tōrea and 1,200 ngutuparore (wrybills) migrating north from the South Island after breeding over the winter.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] During summer months, an estimated 12,000 kuaka (bar-tailed godwits) and 9,000 huahou (red knots) spend summer months in the vicinity of the park.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] Kōtuku ngutupapa (royal spoonbill) also migrate to the area.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] Birdwatchers have identified a total of 86 birds in the park including little shags, and white-faced herons.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] In 2015, a vegetation survey identified 40 native species in Ambury Regional Park, including the nationally vulnerable species *Geranium retrorsum*, and oioi-coastal needle grass, only rarely seen in saline volcanic soil in the Auckland Region.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] There is an extensive history of Māori settlement in the Māngere Mountain area, and there are 95 archaeological sites around the park.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] During the mid-19th century, the area was converted to farmland.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] In 1882, the Ambury English & Co milk company established a creamery on a 260 acres (110 ha) farm on Wallace Road.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] In the late 1960s, the Māngere sewage treatment was established on the shores of the Manukau Harbour.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] Over 500 hectares (1,200 acres) of oxidation ponds were decommissioned, 13 kilometres (8.1 mi) of shoreline were restored, beaches were constructed, and 27,000 trees were planted in New Zealand's largest coastal restoration project, which was officially completed in 2005.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] During the 1960s, the Auckland Regional Authority purchased land adjacent to the Māngere sewage treatment plant as a buffer.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] From une 1973, local community groups were able to user the land, and in 1977 an educational farm was established at the site.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] Ambury Regional Park was officially opened on 26 September 1987.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] In 1985, a fuel pipeline between Marsden Point and Auckland Airport was laid through the park.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] The route is marked by white fenceposts, farm gate tags and triangular marine markers.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] In December 1986, the Ambury Regional Park was the site of a large-scale Mongrel Mob convention, where over 300 members attended, during which gang members helped complete the rock retaining walls along the Manukau waterfront.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] A kidnapping and sexual assault at this event became national news.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] The annual Ambury Farm Day began in 1988.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] By the early 2000s, the park had become a popular school excursion, with 3-4 schools booked per week visiting the working farm.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] A new concept plan for the park was developed in 2009, which included linking it up to nearby walk and cycling tracks.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] By that stage, 25,000 people were visiting the park each year outside of the annual farm day.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] By the late 2010s, around 400,000 people had begun visiting the park annually.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] There are a range of facilities, including public toilets and barbecues.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] The campground can accommodate up to 60 people.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] The park is connected by walkway and cycleway to the Māngere Bridge to Onehunga in the north-east along Kiwi Esplanade, and the Ihumātao to the south.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/ambury-regional-park] It is within walking distance to the nearest bus stop, and the nearest train station is Onehunga railway station.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/aorangi-forest-park] The park has six backcountry huts and a recreational hunting area in the park.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/aorangi-forest-park] There is a large herd of wild red deer and dry conditions, making the park a popular destination for deerstalkers.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/aorangi-forest-park] There is also a small number of goats and pigs in the park.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/aorangi-forest-park] The park can be accessed by foot from several local roads, or via private land with the permission of landowners.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/aorangi-forest-park] A sole-charger presided over the park for several decades, serving as "part caretaker, part sheriff" and de facto police, fire service and fisheries officer.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/aorangi-forest-park] A rare native long-tailed bat was detected in the forest park in March 2020.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/aorangi-forest-park] A 17-year-old hunter was rescued from the park in July 2020 after falling down a cliff.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/aorangi-forest-park] In 2021, James Cameron and his wife committed part of their farmland to establishing a functioning native forest from the Aorangi Forest Park to the foothills of the Remutaka Ranges.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/aorangi-forest-park] Two families became stranded in the park overnight in June 2021 after their four-wheel drive became stuck.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/aorangi-forest-park] The Wairarapa Dark Sky Reserve is an area of 3,665 km2 (1,415 sq mi) that was designated in January 2023.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/aorangi-forest-park] The reserve is certified as an International Dark Sky Reserve, requiring a dark "core" zone that is surrounded by a populated area where policy controls protect the darkness of the core.
[src:aorangi-forest-park/aorangi-forest-park] For the Wairarapa reserve, the dark core is the entire area of the Aorangi Forest Park in the south of the reserve.
